                <note rend="inline" type="source">361.1121 Pyk, Irena Teodozja/22: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-04-30T13:00:00+03:00"
                            >April 30, 1941—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received April 30—11:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>881. Department’s 595, April 28, 5 p.m.<note n="46" xml:id="d921fn46">Not
                        printed.</note> Pyk and Roszkowski left yesterday for Vladivostok where they
                    should be able to make connections with the steamship <hi rend="italic"
                        >Chile</hi> unless the train is late in arriving.<note n="47"
                        xml:id="d921fn47">The train was due to arrive in Vladivostok on May 9, 1941,
                        and the two passengers sailed on the S. S. <hi rend="italic">Chile</hi> of
                        the Johnson Line on May 17.</note> I am informing Ward<note n="48"
                        xml:id="d921fn48">Angus Ivan Ward, American Consul at Vladivostok.</note> of
                    their departure.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
